    "title": "Integrative Close: Assessing Motor Safety and Consumption",
    "objective": "Synthesize the selection of specialized instruments for safety and consumption monitoring by distinguishing between insulation resistance and cumulative energy.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "Selecting the correct instrument requires matching the specific electrical quantity to the technical task at hand.",
      "Remember that standard resistance checks for continuity are different from high-voltage safety 'stress tests' on insulation.",
      "Distinguish clearly between a 'snapshot' of power (Watts) and the 'total tally' of electricity used over a period of time (Energy)."
    ],
    "questionText": "An industrial motor requires a safety inspection followed by a performance review. You must first perform a 'stress test' on the cable insulation to ensure no electricity is leaking, and then you must record the total amount of electricity the motor consumes over a full 12-hour production shift. Identify the two specific instruments required for these tasks and explain why a standard ohmmeter would be unsuitable for the first task.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "Insulation Resistance Tester and Energy Meter (or kWh meter).",
      "An Insulation Resistance Tester is required for the safety check because it uses high voltage to 'stress test' the insulation, whereas a standard ohmmeter uses low battery power and cannot detect insulation leakage.",
      "The Energy Meter is used for the second task because it measures the total consumption over time rather than just an instantaneous power reading."
    ],
    "hint": "Think about which instrument is designed for high-voltage safety checks and which one acts like a 'tally' for electricity usage over several hours."
  }
